# phantom-link — Cursor agent conventions
# ghostlink.lol | AWS serverless URL shortener

## Repo layout
- IaC lives in infra/. Modules are in infra/modules/, instantiated in infra/envs/us-east-1/.
- Lambda handlers live in lambdas/create/ and lambdas/processor/. Packaging output in lambdas/*/package/.
- Frontend assets in frontend/. Service code in services/redirect/.
- Scripts (bash) in scripts/.

## Terraform rules
- Match the existing module structure exactly. Each module in infra/modules/ has its own main.tf,
  variables.tf, and outputs.tf — do not collapse these into a single file.
- Variables must have type and description. No bare variable blocks.
- All resources must include the tags variable if it exists in that module. Never hardcode tag values.
- Never hardcode ARNs, account IDs, region strings, or resource names. Use variables or data sources.
- Never rename an existing resource without explicitly flagging it — a rename is a destroy+recreate
  in Terraform. Call this out clearly before proposing it.
- After any module change, note which infra/envs/us-east-1/ instantiation is affected.
- Provider version constraints live in the env, not in modules. Do not add required_providers
  blocks to modules unless one already exists there.

## Python rules (Lambdas)
- Handlers are in lambdas/create/ and lambdas/processor/. Match existing logging and error-handling
  patterns in those files — read them before writing new code.
- Use structured logging (JSON) if that's what exists. Do not switch logging style.
- Environment variables come from Lambda config, never from hardcoded defaults in handler code.
- If writing tests, use pytest. Mock AWS calls with moto. Do not invent boto3 call signatures —
  check the actual calls in the handler first.

## Bash rules
- All scripts use set -euo pipefail at the top. No exceptions.
- Scripts target Linux/Debian. Do not use macOS-specific flags (e.g. sed -i '' is wrong here).

## Agent behaviour
- Read the relevant existing file(s) before proposing changes to them. Do not guess at variable
  names, resource names, or module interfaces — they are in the files.
- If a value (ARN, name, CIDR, etc.) is not visible in the files you have read, say so and ask.
  Never fabricate a plausible-looking value.
- When proposing a Terraform change, state which resources will be created, modified, or destroyed.
  If you cannot determine this without a plan, say so.
- Show a plan before making multi-file edits. One sentence per file: what changes and why.